{"_id":{"$oid":"5e38da446451c33088c91738"},"photo":{"data":{"$binary":{"base64":"","subType":"00"}},"contentType":"image/jpeg"},"categories":[{"$oid":"5e378d1e080b7e1b34c1bf81"},{"$oid":"5e378d24080b7e1b34c1bf82"}],"tags":[{"$oid":"5e378d46080b7e1b34c1bf84"},{"$oid":"5e378d47080b7e1b34c1bf85"}],"title":"React Suspense with the Fetch API","body":"<h1><br></h1><p><br></p><p><em>Dan Abramov, in response to a React developer asking why Suspense was not responding to the fetch API:</em></p><p><a href=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/practicaldev/image/fetch/s--q0b-SwVL--/c_limit%2Cf_auto%2Cfl_progressive%2Cq_auto%2Cw_880/https://thepracticaldev.s3.amazonaws.com/i/ck9fdk2726r4xr0iqofz.png\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/practicaldev/image/fetch/s--q0b-SwVL--/c_limit%2Cf_auto%2Cfl_progressive%2Cq_auto%2Cw_880/https://thepracticaldev.s3.amazonaws.com/i/ck9fdk2726r4xr0iqofz.png\"></a></p><p>From the legend Dan Abramov himself, we receive such gems as There is [no data fetching solution compatible with React Suspense] that exists yet, and [React Cache] will be the first one, and Suspense is limited to code splitting.</p><p>If I have one thing to tell Daniel Abra Cadabra Abramov, besides how impressed I am with his work, its this:</p><p><a href=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/practicaldev/image/fetch/s--_JG3YqRM--/c_limit%2Cf_auto%2Cfl_progressive%2Cq_auto%2Cw_880/https://thepracticaldev.s3.amazonaws.com/i/n62dtg2hkf31w9aq7k56.png\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/practicaldev/image/fetch/s--_JG3YqRM--/c_limit%2Cf_auto%2Cfl_progressive%2Cq_auto%2Cw_880/https://thepracticaldev.s3.amazonaws.com/i/n62dtg2hkf31w9aq7k56.png\"></a></p><p>Lets reveal the magic behind the curtain that is React Suspense. For educational purposes, Ill cover how I created this package.</p><h1>Shut Up and Give Me the Package! </h1><p>If youre just here for solutions, I dont blame you. You can find&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.npmjs.com/package/fetch-suspense\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">fetch-suspense&nbsp;on NPM</a>&nbsp;and the most extensive documentation of your life on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/CharlesStover/fetch-suspense\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">the GitHub repository</a>.</p><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">import useFetch from 'fetch-suspense';\n\nconst MyComponent = () =&gt; {\n\n  // \"Look! In the example! It's a fetch() request! It's a hook!\"\n  //   \"No! It's kind of like both at the same time.\"\n  const serverResponse = useFetch('/path/to/api', { method: 'POST' });\n\n  // The return value is the body of the server's response.\n  return &lt;div&gt;{serverResponse}&lt;/div&gt;;\n};\n</pre><h1>How Does Suspense Work? </h1><p>A lot of the new React features are built into the React library, as opposed to being external packages, due to the performance benefits of being tightly coupled to the engine that powers React, known as&nbsp;<em>React Fiber</em>.</p><p>Due to React Fibers direct integration with features such as Suspense and hooks, you cannot create a verbatim copy of Suspense in React 16.5. However, you can probably make a less performant polyfill. Ill use some polyfill examples so that you can conceptualize what is happening with Suspense.</p><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">class Suspense extends React.Component {\n\n  constructor(props) {\n    super(props);\n    this.state = {\n      error: null\n    };\n  }\n\n  componentDidCatch(e) {\n    this.setState({ error: e });\n  }\n\n  render() {\n    if (this.state.error) {\n      return this.props.fallback;\n    }\n    return this.props.children;\n  }\n}\n\n/*\n&lt;Suspense fallback={&lt;Loading /&gt;}&gt;\n  &lt;ErrorThrower /&gt;\n&lt;/Suspense&gt;\n*/\n</pre><p>Here is ye olde class component: a fossil remnant of yonder days of React development. The&nbsp;componentDidCatch&nbsp;method is a method that fires whenever a child component throws an error. This allows you to replace uncaught JavaScript errors with a nice UI for your users or otherwise implement important logic during application errors.</p><p>What the above does is mounts Suspense. Since there is no error in the local state, the children of Suspense are mounted too. In this case, the&nbsp;&lt;ErrorThrower /&gt;&nbsp;component is mounted, and it throws an error.</p><p>That error bubbles up to the Suspense instance, where the&nbsp;componentDidCatch&nbsp;method receives it. It handles that error by saving it to its state, causing it to re-render.</p><p>Now that it has rendered with an error in its local state, it no longer renders its children prop, nor the&nbsp;&lt;ErrorThrower /&gt;&nbsp;devil-child as a result. Instead, it renders its&nbsp;fallback&nbsp;prop, which we have set to a nice&nbsp;&lt;Loading /&gt;&nbsp;modal.</p><p>This is how Suspense works now, except instead of throwing errors,&nbsp;<em>JavaScript Promises</em>&nbsp;are thrown. When Suspense catches a Promise, it&nbsp;<em>re-renders</em>, displaying the fallback prop instead of the children that previous threw a Promise. When the Promise resolves, it&nbsp;<em>re-renders again</em>; this time no longer displaying the&nbsp;fallback&nbsp;prop, and instead attempting to re-render the original children, under the presumption that the children are now ready to be rendered without throwing Promises around like theyre meaningless.</p><p>An implementation may look something like this:</p><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">class Suspense extends React.Component {\n\n  constructor(props) {\n    super(props);\n    this.state = {\n      promise: null\n    };\n  }\n\n  componentDidCatch(e) {\n\n    // Drake meme where he says no to errors here.\n    if (e instanceof Error) {\n      throw e;\n    }\n\n    // Drake meme where he says yes to promises here.\n    if (e instanceof Promise) {\n      this.setState({\n        promise: e\n      }, () =&gt; {\n\n        // When the promise finishes, go back to rendering the original children.\n        e.then(() =&gt; {\n          this.setState({ promise: null });\n        });\n      });\n    }\n\n    // This line isn't compatible with the Drake meme format.\n    else {\n      throw e;\n    }\n  }\n\n  render() {\n    if (this.state.promise) {\n      return this.props.fallback;\n    }\n    return this.props.children;\n  }\n}\n\n/*\n&lt;Suspense fallback={&lt;Loading /&gt;}&gt;\n  &lt;PromiseThrower /&gt;\n&lt;/Suspense&gt;\n*/\n</pre><p>Its important to note here that the original children&nbsp;<em>attempted to render</em>&nbsp;before the fallback occurred. It never succeeded.</p><h1>How Does This Apply to Fetch Hooks? </h1><p>What you should have gathered by now is that the fetch hook will need to&nbsp;<em>throw Promises</em>. So it does. That promise is conveniently the fetch request. When Suspense receives that thrown fetch request, it falls back to rendering its&nbsp;fallback&nbsp;prop. When that fetch request completes, it attempts to render the component again.</p><p>Theres just one little tricky dicky problem with thatthe component that threw the fetch request had only&nbsp;<em>attempted</em>&nbsp;to render, but did not succeed. In fact, it is not a part of the&nbsp;fallback&nbsp;at all! It has no instance. It never mounted. It has no state (not even a React hook state); it has no component lifecycle or effects. So when it&nbsp;<em>attempts</em>&nbsp;to render again, how does it know the response of this fetch request? Suspense isnt passing it, and itnot being instantiatedcannot have data attached to it.</p><h1>Golly, How Do You Solve That Conundrum? </h1><p>We solve it with memoization!</p><p>Like that fancy new&nbsp;React.memo&nbsp;feature?</p><p>Yes! (in concept)</p><p>No! (more literally)</p><p>It does not use&nbsp;React.memo, which memoizes React components based on their props. Instead, I use an array of infinite depth to memoize the parameters passed to fetch.</p><p>If a request comes in to fetch data that has been requested before (the second attempt to instantiate after the first attempt failed with a Promise), then it simply returns the data that eventually resolved from the first requests Promise. If this is a fresh request, then we fetch it, cache it in the memoization array, and throw the fetch Promise. By comparing the current request to all entries in the memoization array, we know if we have dispatched this request before.</p><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">const deepEqual = require('deep-equal');\n\ninterface FetchCache {\n  fetch?: Promise&lt;void&gt;;\n  error?: any;\n  init: RequestInit | undefined;\n  input: RequestInfo;\n  response?: any;\n}\n\nconst fetchCaches: FetchCache[] = [];\n\nconst useFetch = (input: RequestInfo, init?: RequestInit | undefined) =&gt; {\n  for (const fetchCache of fetchCaches) {\n\n    // The request hasn't changed since the last call.\n    if (\n      deepEqual(input, fetchCache.input) &amp;&amp;\n      deepEqual(init, fetchCache.init)\n    ) {\n\n      // If we logged an error during this fetch request, THROW the error.\n      if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(fetchCache, 'error')) {\n        throw fetchCache.error;\n      }\n\n      // If we received a response to this fetch request, RETURN it.\n      if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(fetchCache, 'response')) {\n        return fetchCache.response;\n      }\n\n      // If we do not have a response or error, THROW the promise.\n      throw fetchCache.fetch;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // The request is new or has changed.\n  const fetchCache: FetchCache = {\n    fetch:\n\n      // Make the fetch request.\n      fetch(input, init)\n\n        // Parse the response.\n        .then(response =&gt; {\n\n          // Support JSON.\n          if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(response.headers, 'Content-Type')) {\n            return response.json();\n          }\n\n          // Not JSON.\n          return response.text();\n        })\n\n        // Cache the response for when this component\n        //   attempts to render again later.\n        .then(response =&gt; {\n          fetchCache.response = response;\n        })\n\n        // Cache the error for when this component\n        //   attempts to render again later.\n        .catch(e =&gt; {\n          fetchCache.error = e;\n        }),\n    init,\n    input\n  };\n\n  // Add this metadata to the memoization array.\n  fetchCaches.push(fetchCache);\n\n  // Throw the Promise! Suspense to the rescue!\n  throw fetchCache.fetch;\n};\n</pre><h1>That Sounds Like a Memory Leak </h1><p>It can be a feature&nbsp;<em>or</em>&nbsp;a bug!</p><p>But if you think its a bug in your project, you can invalidate the cache by providing a lifespan in milliseconds to the fetch request. Passing a third parameter (a number) to the&nbsp;useFetch&nbsp;hook will tell it to remove the metadata from the memoization array after that many milliseconds. We implement it as easily as so:</p><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">// NEW: lifespan parameter\nconst useFetch = (\n  input: RequestInfo,\n  init?: RequestInit | undefined,\n  lifespan: number = 0\n) =&gt; {\n\n  // ...\n\n  const fetchCache: FetchCache = {\n    fetch:\n\n      // Make the fetch request.\n      fetch(input, init)\n        .then( /* ... */ )\n        .then( /* ... */ )\n        .catch( /* ... */ )\n\n        // Invalidate the cache.\n        .then(() =&gt; {\n\n          // If the user defined a lifespan,\n          if (lifespan &gt; 0) {\n\n            // Wait for the duration of the lifespan,\n            setTimeout(\n              () =&gt; {\n\n                // Find this fetch request and kill it\n                //   from the memoization array.\n                const index = fetchCaches.indexOf(fetchCache);\n                if(index !== -1) {\n                  fetchCaches.splice(index, 1);\n                }\n              },\n              lifespan\n            );\n          }\n        }),\n    // ...\n  };\n  // ...\n};\n\n// ...\n</pre><p>When the fetch has completed, and weve updated the metadata, tick-tock. Its important that the lifespan timer occurs after the&nbsp;catch&nbsp;of the Promise, because we want it to set even if an error occurred.</p><h1>Conclusion </h1><p><br></p><p><br></p>","excerpt":"<h1><br></h1><p><br></p><p><em>Dan Abramov, in response to a React developer asking why Suspense was not responding to the fetch API:</em></p><p><a ...","slug":"react-suspense-with-the-fetch-api","mtitle":"React Suspense with the Fetch API | SEOBLOG","mdesc":"Dan Abramov, in response to a React developer asking why Suspense was not responding to the fetch API:","postedBy":{"$oid":"5e34b3aed5b5ce2d3c3e446f"},"createdAt":{"$date":{"$numberLong":"1580784196894"}},"__v":{"$numberInt":"0"}}

Private fields&nbsp;#</h2><p>Here's how the syntax looks</p><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">\n// private fields must start with '#'\n// and they can't be accessed outside the class block\n\nclass Counter {\n  #x = 0;\n\n  #increment() {\n    this.#x++;\n  }\n\n  onClick() {\n    this.#increment();\n  }\n\n}\n\nconst c = new Counter();\nc.onClick(); // works fine\nc.#increment(); // error\n</pre><p><br></p><h2>2. Optional Chaining</h2><p>Ever had to access a property nested a few levels inside an object and got the infamous error&nbsp;Cannot read property 'stop' of undefined. Then you change your code to handle every possible&nbsp;undefined&nbsp;object in the chain, like:</p><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">const stop = please &amp;&amp; please.make &amp;&amp; please.make.it &amp;&amp; please.make.it.stop;\n\n// or use a library like 'object-path'\nconst stop = objectPath.get(please, \"make.it.stop\");\n\n</pre><p>With optional chaining, soon you'll be able to get the same done writing:</p><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">const stop = please?.make?.it?.stop;\n\n</pre>","excerpt":"<h2>1. {"_id":{"$oid":"5e44caac748f2a2bc4179d12"},"photo":{"data":{"$binary":{"base64":"","subType":"00"}},"contentType":"image/jpeg"},"categories":[{"$oid":"5e3f9275b24f7815a8941231"},{"$oid":"5e3f92a4b24f7815a8941237"},{"$oid":"5e3f92abb24f7815a8941238"},{"$oid":"5e3f92b7b24f7815a894123a"},{"$oid":"5e3f92b4b24f7815a8941239"}],"tags":[{"$oid":"5e3f924ab24f7815a894122e"}],"title":"New in React 16.8","body":"<h2><strong>What is React?</strong></h2><p>React is a library by Facebook that allows you to create super performant user interfaces. React allows you to disintegrate a user interface into components, a functional unit of an interface. By composing components together, you can create UIs that scale well and deliver performance.</p><p>What sets React apart is its feature set.</p><p>1. The Virtual DOM -&nbsp;An in-memory representation of the DOM and a reconciliation algorithm that is at the heart of Reacts performance.</p><p>2. Declarative Programming &amp; State -&nbsp;State is the data that describes what your component renders as its content. You simply update the state and React manages the rest of the process that leads to the view getting updated. This is known as declarative programming where you simply describe your views in terms of data that it has to show.</p><p>3. Components -&nbsp;Everything that you build with React, is known as a component. By breaking down UIs into functional and atomic pieces, you can compose together interfaces that scale well. The image below demonstrates a login interface which has been composed together using three components.</p><p><img src=\"https://d6vdma9166ldh.cloudfront.net/media/images/1553068416448-What's-new-in-React-16.8-1.jpg\"></p><p>4. JSX -&nbsp;The render method inside a class component or the function component itself allows you to use JSX, which is like an XML language that incorporates JavaScript expressions. Internally, JSX is compiled into efficient render functions.</p><p>5. Synthetic Events -&nbsp;Browsers handle events differently. React wraps browser specific implementations into Synthetic Events, which are dispatched on user interaction. React takes care of the underlying browser specific implementation internally.</p><p>6. Props -&nbsp;Components can either fetch data from an API and store in the local state, or they can ingest data using props, which are like inlets into a prop. Components re-render if the data in the props update</p>","excerpt":"<h2><strong>What is React?</strong></h2><p>React is a library by Facebook that allows you to create super performant user interfaces.
